03959nam a22004935i 9780300157437DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001574377 a10.12987/97803001574372doi  a(DE-B1597)611950  a(OCoLC)1306540000  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809/.927222/eng1 aKuznets, Lois Rostow, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhen Toys Come Alive :bNarratives of Animation, Metamorphosis, and Development /cLois Rostow Kuznets. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2022] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- t1. An Introduction to My World of Literary Toys -- t2. Toys: Their First Ten Thousand Years -- t3. On the Couch with Calvin, Hobbes, and Winnie the Pooh -- t4. Coming out in Flesh and Blood -- t5. Where Have All the Young Men Gone? -- t6. The Doll Connection -- t7. Magic Settings, Transitional Space -- t8. The Animal-Toy League -- t9. Beyond the Last Visible Toy -- t10. Life(size) Endowments: Monsters, Automata, Robots, Cyborgs -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the eighteenth century, toys have had an important place in European and American stories written for children and adults, often taking on a secret, sensual, even carnivalesque life of their own. In this groundbreaking work, Lois Rostow Kuznets studies the role of toy characters in works ranging from older classics like Pinocchio, Winnie the Pooh, and The Velveteen Rabbit, through modern texts like The Mouse and His Child and the popular comic strip Calvin and Hobbes, to the latest science fiction featuring robots and cyborgs.Using a variety of intertextual critical approaches, including feminist theory, neo-Freudian Winnicott play analysis, structuralism, and neo-Marxism, Kuznets focuses on how toy characters, like children's play, can be associated with deep human needs, desires, and fears. Anxiety about being "real"—an autonomous subject rather than an object—permeates many of the texts Kuznets analyzes. Toy fantasies also raise existential issues of power: what it means either to dominate or to be dominated by more powerful beings, and what dangers might lie in the transformation of a toy into a living being—an act of human creativity that represents a challenge to divine creation. Kuznets concludes that although many of these texts subvert conformity on an individual level, they also tend to evoke a romantic nostalgia that supports the underlying values and hierarchies of a patriarchal society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030005645740uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015743740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300157437423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300157437/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles